# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: gatling
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:gatling/gatling-software] The software is designed to be used as a load testing tool for analyzing and measuring the performance of a variety of services, with a focus on web applications, application programming interfaces (APIs), and microservices.
[src:gatling/gatling-software] Gatling was mentioned twice in ThoughtWorks Technology Radar, in 2013 and 2014, "as a tool worth trying", with an emphasis on "the interesting premise of *treating your performance tests as production code*".
[src:gatling/gatling-software] The latest minor release is Gatling 3.14, published on May 12, 2025.
[src:gatling/gatling-software] Gatling started as an open-source project in 2012 by Stéphane Landelle, while he was the chief technology officer (CTO) of a French IT consulting firm, eBusiness Information.
[src:gatling/gatling-software] In 2015 a dedicated company named "Gatling Corp" to develop a commercial product for load test orchestration and collaboration.
[src:gatling/gatling-software] The first version of Gatling Enterprise (originally named FrontLine) was released in 2016.
[src:gatling/gatling-software] The company is based in Bagneux, France, near Paris.
[src:gatling/gatling-software] Gatling Corp is a member of Systematic Paris-Region, an Île-de-France business cluster created in 2005, devoted to complex systems and ICT.
[src:gatling/gatling-software] Systematic Paris-Region gathers large groups, SMEs, universities and research labs to promote digital innovation.
[src:gatling/gatling-software] Gatling is a member of Systematic's Open Source Working Group and was elected member of Systematic's board of directors, as a representative of SMEs, in November 2016.
[src:gatling/gatling-software] The company took part in some events, like the Paris Open Source Summit (POSS, 2015, 2016 and 2017 editions), Liferay's 2016 Symposium, Java User Group (JUG)'s meetings, the Paris Gatling User Group and the New York Gatling User Group.
[src:gatling/gatling-software] Gatling consists of an open-source core and an enterprise orchestration and collaboration platform.
[src:gatling/gatling-software] Gatling implemented a fully new architecture for a performance testing tool, in order to be more resource efficient.
[src:gatling/gatling-software] It makes it possible to simulate a high number of requests per second with a single machine.
[src:gatling/gatling-software] Gatling comes with an HTTP web recorder to bootstrap a simulation.
[src:gatling/gatling-software] The HTTP recorder can be used to directly capture browser actions or convert .har files to load test scenarios.
[src:gatling/gatling-software] Gatling Studio is a desktop tool that records browser sessions and converts them into Gatling load test scripts.
[src:gatling/gatling-software] It captures HTTP interactions — including headers, payloads, and timing — from a live browser session or an imported HAR file, filters out static and third-party requests, and generates Java (Maven) code representing the recorded user flow.
[src:gatling/gatling-software] The exported project can be run locally with Gatling Community Edition or deployed through Gatling Enterprise Edition.
[src:gatling/gatling-software] Gatling is provided with a simple and lightweight Domain-specific language, in which simulations and scenarios are coded.
[src:gatling/gatling-software] This allows users to add custom behavior through many hooks.
[src:gatling/gatling-software] This makes simulation scripts readable and easy to maintain.
[src:gatling/gatling-software] In 2024 Gatling introduced a new DSL (SDK) for JavaScript and TypeScript.
[src:gatling/gatling-software] The JavaScript and TypeScript SDK uses GraalVM to translate JavaScript code to Java and execute load tests on a Java virtual machine (JVM).
[src:gatling/gatling-software] Adding JavaScript and TypeScript support made Gatling the first polyglot load testing tool in the market.
[src:gatling/gatling-software] At the end of each test, Gatling generates a static HTML report.
[src:gatling/gatling-software] Gatling incorporates several AI-assisted features.
[src:gatling/gatling-software] An IDE plugin can generate test simulations from natural language prompts and convert scripts from tools such as JMeter and LoadRunner.
[src:gatling/gatling-software] The platform can produce plain-language summaries of completed test runs, highlighting anomalies and regressions.
[src:gatling/gatling-software] A Model Context Protocol (MCP) server allows compatible AI coding agents to configure and launch tests from within a development environment.
[src:gatling/gatling-software] The platform also supports protocols associated with large language model (LLM) workloads, including Server-Sent Events (SSE) and WebSockets.
[src:gatling/gatling-software] Gatling documentation states that it is protocol agnostic, which makes it possible to implement other protocols' support.
[src:gatling/gatling-software] Gatling comes out with official and community plugins.
[src:gatling/gatling-software] Automation with Gatling is related to its simulations' maintainability.
[src:gatling/gatling-software] The integration with other developer tools, especially in the DevOps lifecycle, makes it possible to create performance tests at scale, that is to say to fully automate the execution of performance testing campaigns in the software development process.
[src:gatling/gatling-software] Gatling is published under Apache License 2.0, a permissive free software license written by the Apache Software Foundation (ASF).
[src:gatling/gatling-software] The source code is accessible on GitHub.
[src:gatling/gatling-software] Gatling Enterprise is the commercial version of Gatling.
[src:gatling/gatling-software] It is proprietary software, distributed by Gatling Corp.
[src:gatling/load-testing] Many types of machinery, engines, structures, and motors are load tested.
[src:gatling/load-testing] The load may be at a designated safe working load (SWL), full load, or at an aggravated level of load.
[src:gatling/load-testing] The governing contract, technical specification or test method contains the details of conducting the test.
[src:gatling/load-testing] The purpose of a mechanical load test is to verify that all the component parts of a structure including materials, base-fixings are fit for task and loading it is designed for.
[src:gatling/load-testing] The *Supply of Machinery (Safety) Regulation 1992 UK* state that load testing is undertaken before the equipment is put into service for the first time.
[src:gatling/load-testing] Performance testing applies a safe working load (SWL), or other specified load, for a designated time in a governing test method, specification, or contract.
[src:gatling/load-testing] Under the *Lifting Operations and Lifting Equipment Regulations 1998 UK* load testing after the initial test is required if a major component is replaced, if the item is moved from one location to another or as dictated by the competent person.
[src:gatling/load-testing] The term *load testing* or stress testing is used in different ways in the professional software testing community.
[src:gatling/load-testing] *Load testing* generally refers to the practice of modeling the expected usage of a software program by simulating multiple users accessing the program concurrently.
[src:gatling/page] Test scenarios are defined as code using expressive SDKs for Java, JavaScript, TypeScript, Scala, or Kotlin, making them easy to read, version, and maintain as part of your development workflow.
[src:gatling/page] Gatling’s architecture is fully asynchronous.
[src:gatling/page] Virtual users are modeled as lightweight messages rather than threads, allowing you to simulate thousands of concurrent users with minimal system resources, ideal for modern, high-scale applications.
[src:gatling/page] While Gatling offers robust support for **HTTP** out of the box, the load engine is protocol-agnostic.
[src:gatling/page] It also ships with **JMS** support and can be extended to handle other protocols.
[src:gatling/page] Try **Gatling Enterprise Edition** free for 14 days, no credit card required.
[src:gatling/page] Want to learn more about what Gatling Enterprise Edition offers?
