[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] Scala source code can be compiled to JVM bytecode and run on a Java virtual machine (JVM).
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] Scala can also be transpiled to JavaScript to run in a browser, or compiled directly to a native executable using Clang.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] When running on the JVM, Scala provides language interoperability with Java so that libraries written in either language may be referenced directly in Scala or Java code.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] Like Java, Scala is object-oriented, and uses a syntax termed *curly-brace* which is similar to the language C.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] Since Scala 3, there is also an option to use the off-side rule (indenting) to structure blocks, and its use is advised.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] Martin Odersky has said that this turned out to be the most productive change introduced in Scala 3.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] Unlike Java, Scala has many features of functional programming languages (like Scheme, Standard ML, and Haskell), including currying, immutability, lazy evaluation, and pattern matching.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] The name Scala is a portmanteau of *scalable* and *language*, signifying that it is designed to grow with the demands of its users.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] The design of Scala started in 2001 at the École Polytechnique Fédérale de Lausanne (EPFL) (in Lausanne, Switzerland) by Martin Odersky.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] It followed on from work on Funnel, a programming language combining ideas from functional programming and Petri nets.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] Odersky formerly worked on Generic Java, and javac, Sun's Java compiler.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] After an internal release in late 2003, Scala was released publicly in early 2004 on the Java platform, A second version (v2.0) followed in March 2006.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] On 17 January 2011, the Scala team won a five-year research grant of over €2.3 million from the European Research Council.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] On 12 May 2011, Odersky and collaborators launched Typesafe Inc.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] (later renamed Lightbend Inc.), a company to provide commercial support, training, and services for Scala.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] Typesafe received a $3 million investment in 2011 from Greylock Partners.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] Scala runs on the Java platform (Java virtual machine) and is compatible with existing Java programs.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] The reference Scala software distribution, including compiler and libraries, is released under the Apache license.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] Scala Native is a Scala compiler that targets the LLVM compiler infrastructure to create executable code that uses a lightweight managed runtime, which uses the Boehm garbage collector.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] The project is led by Denys Shabalin and had its first release, 0.1, on 14 March 2017.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] Development of Scala Native began in 2015 with a goal of being faster than just-in-time compilation for the JVM by eliminating the initial runtime compilation of code and also providing the ability to call native routines directly.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] A reference Scala compiler targeting the .NET Framework and its Common Language Runtime was released in June 2004, but was officially dropped in 2012.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] Unlike the stand-alone Hello World application for Java, there is no class declaration and nothing is declared to be static.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] This is analogous to the process for compiling and running Java code.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] Indeed, Scala's compiling and executing model is identical to that of Java, making it compatible with Java build tools such as Apache Ant.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] Scala includes an interactive shell and scripting support.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] The following example shows the differences between Java and Scala syntax.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] These syntactic relaxations are designed to allow support for domain-specific languages.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] The following example contrasts the definition of classes in Java and Scala.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] Scala has the same compiling model as Java and C#, namely separate compiling and dynamic class loading, so that Scala code can call Java libraries.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] Scala's operational characteristics are the same as Java's.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] The Scala compiler generates byte code that is nearly identical to that generated by the Java compiler.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] In fact, Scala code can be decompiled to readable Java code, with the exception of certain constructor operations.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] To the Java virtual machine (JVM), Scala code and Java code are indistinguishable.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] The only difference is one extra runtime library, `scala-library.jar`.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] Scala adds a large number of features compared with Java, and has some fundamental differences in its underlying model of expressions and types, which make the language theoretically cleaner and eliminate several *corner cases* in Java.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] From the Scala perspective, this is practically important because several added features in Scala are also available in C#.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] As mentioned above, Scala has a good deal of syntactic flexibility, compared with Java.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] By themselves, these may seem like questionable choices, but collectively they serve the purpose of allowing domain-specific languages to be defined in Scala without needing to extend the compiler.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] For example, Erlang's special syntax for sending a message to an actor, i.e.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] `actor ! message` can be (and is) implemented in a Scala library without needing language extensions.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] Java makes a sharp distinction between primitive types (e.g.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] `int` and `boolean`) and reference types (any class).
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] Only reference types are part of the inheritance scheme, deriving from `java.lang.Object`.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] In Scala, all types inherit from a top-level class `Any`, whose immediate children are `AnyVal` (value types, such as `Int` and `Boolean`) and `AnyRef` (reference types, as in Java).
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] This means that the Java distinction between primitive types and boxed types (e.g.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] `Integer`) is not present in Scala; boxing and unboxing is completely transparent to the user.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] Scala 2.10 allows for new value types to be defined by the user.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] Instead of the Java "foreach" loops for looping through an iterator, Scala has `for`-expressions, which are similar to list comprehensions in languages such as Haskell, or a combination of list comprehensions and generator expressions in Python.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] For-expressions using the `yield` keyword allow a new collection to be generated by iterating over an existing one, returning a new collection of the same type.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] They are translated by the compiler into a series of `map`, `flatMap` and `filter` calls.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] Where `yield` is not used, the code approximates to an imperative-style loop, by translating to `foreach`.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] (The expression `1 to 25` is not special syntax.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] Expression `(mention, times) <- mentions` is an example of pattern matching (see below).
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] Iterating over a map returns a set of key-value tuples, and pattern-matching allows the tuples to easily be destructured into separate variables for the key and value.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] Similarly, the result of the comprehension also returns key-value tuples, which are automatically built back up into a map because the source object (from the variable `mentions`) is a map.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] If `mentions` instead held a list, set, array or other collection of tuples, exactly the same code above would yield a new collection of the same type.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] While supporting all of the object-oriented features available in Java (and in fact, augmenting them in various ways), Scala also provides a large number of capabilities that are normally found only in functional programming languages.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] Together, these features allow Scala programs to be written in an almost completely functional style and also allow functional and object-oriented styles to be mixed.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] Unlike C or Java, but similar to languages such as Lisp, Scala makes no distinction between statements and expressions.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] All statements are in fact expressions that evaluate to some value.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] Functions that would be declared as returning `void` in C or Java, and statements like `while` that logically do not return a value, are in Scala considered to return the type `Unit`, which is a singleton type, with only one object of that type.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] Functions and operators that never return at all (e.g. the `throw` operator or a function that always exits non-locally using an exception) logically have return type `Nothing`, a special type containing no objects; that is, a bottom type, i.e. a subclass of every possible type.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] Similarly, an `if-then-else` "statement" is actually an expression, which produces a value, i.e. the result of evaluating one of the two branches.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] For similar reasons, `return` statements are unnecessary in Scala, and in fact are discouraged.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] As in Lisp, the last expression in a block of code is the value of that block of code, and if the block of code is the body of a function, it will be returned by the function.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] Due to type inference, the type of variables, function return values, and many other expressions can typically be omitted, as the compiler can deduce it.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] Examples are `val x = "foo"` (for an immutable constant or immutable object) or `var x = 1.5` (for a variable whose value can later be changed).
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] Type inference in Scala is essentially local, in contrast to the more global Hindley-Milner algorithm used in Haskell, ML and other more purely functional languages.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] This is done to facilitate object-oriented programming.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] The result is that certain types still need to be declared (most notably, function parameters, and the return types of recursive functions), e.g.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] In Scala, functions are objects, and a convenient syntax exists for specifying anonymous functions.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] An example is the expression `x => x < 2`, which specifies a function with one parameter, that compares its argument to see if it is less than 2.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] It is equivalent to the Lisp form `(lambda (x) (< x 2))`.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] Neither the type of x nor the return type need be explicitly specified, and can generally be inferred by type inference; but they can be explicitly specified, e.g., as `(x: Int) => x < 2` or even `(x: Int) => (x < 2): Boolean`.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] Anonymous functions behave as true closures in that they automatically capture any variables that are lexically available in the environment of the enclosing function.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] Those variables will be available even after the enclosing function returns, and unlike in the case of Java's *anonymous inner classes* do not need to be declared as final.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] Scala enforces a distinction between immutable and mutable variables.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] Mutable variables are declared using the `var` keyword and immutable values are declared using the `val` keyword.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] A variable declared using the `val` keyword cannot be reassigned in the same way that a variable declared using the `final` keyword can't be reassigned in Java.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] `val`s are only shallowly immutable, that is, an object referenced by a val is not guaranteed to itself be immutable.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] Immutable classes are encouraged by convention however, and the Scala standard library provides a rich set of immutable collection classes.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] Scala provides mutable and immutable variants of most collection classes, and the immutable version is always used unless the mutable version is explicitly imported.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] The immutable variants are persistent data structures that always return an updated copy of an old object instead of updating the old object destructively in place.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] An example of this is immutable linked lists where prepending an element to a list is done by returning a new list node consisting of the element and a reference to the list tail.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] Appending an element to a list can only be done by prepending all elements in the old list to a new list with only the new element.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] In the same way, inserting an element in the middle of a list will copy the first half of the list, but keep a reference to the second half of the list.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] This allows for very easy concurrency — no locks are needed as no shared objects are ever modified.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] Evaluation is strict ("eager") by default.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] In other words, Scala evaluates expressions as soon as they are available, rather than as needed.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] However, it is possible to declare a variable non-strict ("lazy") with the `lazy` keyword, meaning that the code to produce the variable's value will not be evaluated until the first time the variable is referenced.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] Non-strict collections of various types also exist (such as the type `Stream`, a non-strict linked list), and any collection can be made non-strict with the `view` method.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] Non-strict collections provide a good semantic fit to things like server-produced data, where the evaluation of the code to generate later elements of a list (that in turn triggers a request to a server, possibly located somewhere else on the web) only happens when the elements are actually needed.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] Functional programming languages commonly provide tail call optimization to allow for extensive use of recursion without stack overflow problems.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] Limitations in JVM bytecode complicate tail call optimization on the JVM.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] In general, a function that calls itself with a tail call can be optimized, but mutually recursive functions cannot.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] Trampolines have been suggested as a workaround.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] Trampoline support has been provided by the Scala library with the object `scala.util.control.TailCalls` since Scala 2.8.0 (released 14 July 2010).
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] A function may optionally be annotated with `@tailrec`, in which case it will not compile unless it is tail recursive.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] An example of this optimization could be implemented using the factorial definition.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] This ensures tail call optimization and thus prevents a stack overflow error.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] Scala has built-in support for pattern matching, which can be thought of as a more sophisticated, extensible version of a switch statement, where arbitrary data types can be matched (rather than just simple types like integers, Booleans and strings), including arbitrary nesting.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] A special type of class known as a *case class* is provided, which includes automatic support for pattern matching and can be used to model the algebraic data types used in many functional programming languages.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] The idea here is that we partition a list into the elements less than a pivot and the elements not less, recursively sort each part, and paste the results together with the pivot in between.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] This uses the same divide-and-conquer strategy of mergesort and other fast sorting algorithms.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] The `match` operator is used to do pattern matching on the object stored in `list`.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] Each `case` expression is tried in turn to see if it will match, and the first match determines the result.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] In this case, `Nil` only matches the literal object `Nil`, but `pivot :: tail` matches a non-empty list, and simultaneously *destructures* the list according to the pattern given.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] In this case, the associated code will have access to a local variable named `pivot` holding the head of the list, and another variable `tail` holding the tail of the list.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] These variables are read-only, and are semantically very similar to variable bindings established using the `let` operator in Lisp and Scheme.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] Pattern matching also happens in local variable declarations.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] In this case, the return value of the call to `tail.partition` is a tuple — in this case, two lists.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] (Tuples differ from other types of containers, e.g. lists, in that they are always of fixed size and the elements can be of differing types — although here they are both the same.) Pattern matching is the easiest way of fetching the two parts of the tuple.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] The form `_ < pivot` is a declaration of an anonymous function with a placeholder variable; see the section above on anonymous functions.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] The list operators `::` (which adds an element onto the beginning of a list, similar to `cons` in Lisp and Scheme) and `:::` (which appends two lists together, similar to `append` in Lisp and Scheme) both appear.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] Despite appearances, there is nothing "built-in" about either of these operators.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] As specified above, any string of symbols can serve as function name, and a method applied to an object can be written "infix"-style without the period or parentheses.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] In the pattern-matching example above, the body of the `match` operator is a partial function, which consists of a series of `case` expressions, with the first matching expression prevailing, similar to the body of a switch statement.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] Finally, a partial function can be used alone, and the result of calling it is equivalent to doing a `match` over it.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] Here a read-only *variable* is declared whose type is a function from lists of integers to lists of integers, and bind it to a partial function.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] Scala is a pure object-oriented language in the sense that every value is an object.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] Data types and behaviors of objects are described by classes and traits.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] Class abstractions are extended by subclassing and by a flexible mixin-based composition mechanism to avoid the problems of multiple inheritance.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] Traits are Scala's replacement for Java's interfaces.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] Interfaces in Java versions under 8 are highly restricted, able only to contain abstract function declarations.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] This has led to criticism that providing convenience methods in interfaces is awkward (the same methods must be reimplemented in every implementation), and extending a published interface in a backwards-compatible way is impossible.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] Traits are similar to mixin classes in that they have nearly all the power of a regular abstract class, lacking only class parameters (Scala's equivalent to Java's constructor parameters), since traits are always mixed in with a class.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] The `super` operator behaves specially in traits, allowing traits to be chained using composition in addition to inheritance.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] In other words, the call to `draw` first executed the code in `TitleDecoration` (the last trait mixed in), then (through the `super()` calls) threaded back through the other mixed-in traits and eventually to the code in `Window`, *even though none of the traits inherited from one another*.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] This is similar to the decorator pattern, but is more concise and less error-prone, as it doesn't require explicitly encapsulating the parent window, explicitly forwarding functions whose implementation isn't changed, or relying on run-time initialization of entity relationships.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] In other languages, a similar effect could be achieved at compile-time with a long linear chain of implementation inheritance, but with the disadvantage compared to Scala that one linear inheritance chain would have to be declared for each possible combination of the mix-ins.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] Scala is equipped with an expressive static type system that mostly enforces the safe and coherent use of abstractions.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] This makes most static type declarations optional.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] Static types need not be explicitly declared unless a compiler error indicates the need.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] In practice, some static type declarations are included for the sake of code clarity.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] A common technique in Scala, known as "enrich my library" (originally termed "pimp my library" by Martin Odersky in 2006; concerns were raised about this phrasing due to its negative connotations and immaturity), allows new methods to be used as if they were added to existing types.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] This is similar to the C# concept of extension methods but more powerful, because the technique is not limited to adding methods and can, for instance, be used to implement new interfaces.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] In Scala, this technique involves declaring an implicit conversion from the type "receiving" the method to a new type (typically, a class) that wraps the original type and provides the additional method.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] If a method cannot be found for a given type, the compiler automatically searches for any applicable implicit conversions to types that provide the method in question.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] This technique allows new methods to be added to an existing class using an add-on library such that only code that *imports* the add-on library gets the new functionality, and all other code is unaffected.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] Importing the members of `MyExtensions` brings the implicit conversion to extension class `IntPredicates` into scope.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] Scala's standard library includes support for futures and promises, in addition to the standard Java concurrency APIs.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] Originally, it also included support for the actor model, which is now available as a separate source-available platform Akka licensed by Lightbend Inc.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] Akka actors may be distributed or combined with software transactional memory (*transactors*).
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] Alternative communicating sequential processes (CSP) implementations for channel-based message passing are Communicating Scala Objects, or simply via JCSP.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] An Actor is like a thread instance with a mailbox.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] It can be created by `system.actorOf`, overriding the `receive` method to receive messages and using the `!` (exclamation point) method to send a message.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] The following example shows an EchoServer that can receive messages and then print them.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] Scala also comes with built-in support for data-parallel programming in the form of Parallel Collections integrated into its Standard Library since version 2.9.0.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] The following example shows how to use Parallel Collections to improve performance.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] Besides futures and promises, actor support, and data parallelism, Scala also supports asynchronous programming with software transactional memory, and event streams.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] The most well-known open-source cluster-computing solution written in Scala is Apache Spark.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] Additionally, Apache Kafka, the publish–subscribe message queue popular with Spark and other stream processing technologies, is written in Scala.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] There are several ways to test code in Scala.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] ScalaTest supports multiple testing styles and can integrate with Java-based testing frameworks.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] ScalaCheck is a library similar to Haskell's QuickCheck. specs2 is a library for writing executable software specifications.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] ScalaMock provides support for testing high-order and curried functions.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p01] JUnit and TestNG are popular testing frameworks written in Java.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p02] Scala is often compared with Groovy and Clojure, two other programming languages also using the JVM.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p02] Substantial differences between these languages exist in the type system, in the extent to which each language supports object-oriented and functional programming, and in the similarity of their syntax to that of Java.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p02] Scala is statically typed, while both Groovy and Clojure are dynamically typed.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p02] This makes the type system more complex and difficult to understand but allows almost all type errors to be caught at compile-time and can result in significantly faster execution.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p02] By contrast, dynamic typing requires more testing to ensure program correctness, and thus is generally slower, to allow greater programming flexibility and simplicity.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p02] Regarding speed differences, current versions of Groovy and Clojure allow optional type annotations to help programs avoid the overhead of dynamic typing in cases where types are practically static.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p02] This overhead is further reduced when using recent versions of the JVM, which has been enhanced with an *invoke dynamic* instruction for methods that are defined with dynamically typed arguments.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p02] These advances reduce the speed gap between static and dynamic typing, although a statically typed language, like Scala, is still the preferred choice when execution efficiency is very important.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p02] Regarding programming paradigms, Scala inherits the object-oriented model of Java and extends it in various ways.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p02] Groovy, while also strongly object-oriented, is more focused in reducing verbosity.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p02] In Clojure, object-oriented programming is deemphasised with functional programming being the main strength of the language.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p02] Scala also has many functional programming facilities, including features found in advanced functional languages like Haskell, and tries to be agnostic between the two paradigms, letting the developer choose between the two paradigms or, more frequently, some combination thereof.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p02] Regarding syntax similarity with Java, Scala inherits much of Java's syntax, as is the case with Groovy.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p02] Clojure on the other hand follows the Lisp syntax, which is different in both appearance and philosophy.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p02] Back in 2013, when Scala was in version 2.10, the ThoughtWorks Technology Radar, which is an opinion based biannual report of a group of senior technologists, recommended Scala adoption in its languages and frameworks category.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p02] In the 2018 edition of the *State of Java* survey, which collected data from 5160 developers on various Java-related topics, Scala places third in terms of use of alternative languages on the JVM.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p02] Relative to the prior year's edition of the survey, Scala's use among alternative JVM languages fell from 28.4% to 21.5%, overtaken by Kotlin, which rose from 11.4% in 2017 to 28.8% in 2018.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p02] The Popularity of Programming Language Index, which tracks searches for language tutorials, ranked Scala 15th in April 2018 with a small downward trend, and 17th in Jan 2021.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p02] This makes Scala the 3rd most popular JVM-based language after Java and Kotlin, ranked 12th.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p02] The RedMonk Programming Language Rankings, which establishes rankings based on the number of GitHub projects and questions asked on Stack Overflow, in January 2021 ranked Scala 14th.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p02] Here, Scala was placed inside a second-tier group of languages–ahead of Go, PowerShell, and Haskell, and behind Swift, Objective-C, TypeScript, and R.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p02] The TIOBE index of programming language popularity employs internet search engine rankings and similar publication counting to determine language popularity.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p02] In September 2021, it showed Scala in 31st place.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p02] In this ranking, Scala was ahead of Haskell (38th) and Erlang, but below Go (14th), Swift (15th), and Perl (19th).
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p02] As of 2022, JVM-based languages such as Clojure, Groovy, and Scala are highly ranked, but still significantly less popular than the original Java language, which is usually ranked in the top three places.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p02] In November 2011, Yammer moved away from Scala for reasons that included the learning curve for new team members and incompatibility from one version of the Scala compiler to the next.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p02] In March 2015, former VP of the Platform Engineering group at Twitter Raffi Krikorian, stated that he would not have chosen Scala in 2011 due to its learning curve.
[src:gatling/scala-programming-language-p02] The same month, LinkedIn SVP Kevin Scott stated their decision to "minimize [their] dependence on Scala".
[src:gatling/software-performance-testing] In software quality assurance, **performance testing** is in general a testing practice performed to determine how a system performs in terms of responsiveness and stability under a particular workload.
[src:gatling/software-performance-testing] It can also serve to investigate, measure, validate or verify other quality attributes of the system, such as scalability, reliability and resource usage.
[src:gatling/software-performance-testing] Performance testing, a subset of performance engineering, is a computer science practice which strives to build performance standards into the implementation, design and architecture of a system.
[src:gatling/software-performance-testing] Tests examining the behavior under load are categorized into six basic types: Baseline test, load test, stress test, soak test, smoke test or isolation test.
[src:gatling/software-performance-testing] Additionally to these basic types, configuration testing and Internet testing can be done.
[src:gatling/software-performance-testing] Baseline testing is used to create a comparison point for other types of tests, e.g., for a stress test.
[src:gatling/software-performance-testing] By measuring how the system reacts in a "best case", for example only 5 parallel users, the other test types can be used to compare how the performance degrades in the worst case.
[src:gatling/software-performance-testing] Load testing is the simplest form of performance testing.
[src:gatling/software-performance-testing] A load test is usually conducted to understand the behavior of the system under a specific expected load.
[src:gatling/software-performance-testing] This load can be the expected concurrent number of users on the application performing a specific number of transactions within the set duration.
[src:gatling/software-performance-testing] This test will give out the response times of all the important business critical transactions.
[src:gatling/software-performance-testing] The database, application server, etc. are also monitored during the test, this will assist in identifying bottlenecks in the application software and the hardware that the software is installed on.
[src:gatling/software-performance-testing] Stress testing is normally used to understand the upper limits of capacity within the system.
[src:gatling/software-performance-testing] This kind of test is done to determine the system's robustness in terms of extreme load and helps application administrators to determine if the system will perform sufficiently if the current load goes well above the expected maximum.
[src:gatling/software-performance-testing] Soak testing, also known as endurance testing or stability testing, is usually done to determine if the system can sustain the continuous expected load.
[src:gatling/software-performance-testing] During soak tests, memory utilization is monitored to detect potential leaks.
[src:gatling/software-performance-testing] Also important, but often overlooked is performance degradation, i.e. to ensure that the throughput and/or response times after some long period of sustained activity are as good as or better than at the beginning of the test.
[src:gatling/software-performance-testing] It essentially involves applying a significant load to a system for an extended, significant period of time.
[src:gatling/software-performance-testing] The goal is to discover how the system behaves under sustained use.
[src:gatling/software-performance-testing] Isolation testing is not unique to performance testing but involves repeating a test execution that resulted in a system problem.
[src:gatling/software-performance-testing] Such testing can often isolate and confirm the fault domain.
[src:gatling/software-performance-testing] Rather than testing for performance from a load perspective, tests are created to determine the effects of configuration changes to the system's components on the system's performance and behavior.
[src:gatling/software-performance-testing] A common example would be experimenting with different methods of load-balancing.
[src:gatling/software-performance-testing] This is a relatively new form of performance testing when global applications such as Facebook, Google and Wikipedia, are performance tested from load generators that are placed on the actual target continent whether physical machines or cloud VMs.
[src:gatling/software-performance-testing] These tests usually require an immense amount of preparation and monitoring to be executed successfully.
[src:gatling/software-performance-testing] Many performance tests are undertaken without setting sufficiently realistic, goal-oriented performance goals.
[src:gatling/software-performance-testing] The first question from a business perspective should always be, "why are we performance-testing?".
[src:gatling/software-performance-testing] These considerations are part of the business case of the testing.
[src:gatling/software-performance-testing] If a system identifies end-users by some form of log-in procedure then a concurrency goal is highly desirable.
[src:gatling/software-performance-testing] By definition this is the largest number of concurrent system users that the system is expected to support at any given moment.
[src:gatling/software-performance-testing] The work-flow of a scripted transaction may impact true concurrency especially if the iterative part contains the log-in and log-out activity.
[src:gatling/software-performance-testing] If the system has no concept of end-users, then performance goal is likely to be based on a maximum throughput or transaction rate.
[src:gatling/software-performance-testing] This refers to the time taken for one system node to respond to the request of another.
[src:gatling/software-performance-testing] A simple example would be a HTTP 'GET' request from browser client to web server.
[src:gatling/software-performance-testing] In terms of response time this is what all load testing tools actually measure.
[src:gatling/software-performance-testing] It may be relevant to set server response time goals between all nodes of the system.
[src:gatling/software-performance-testing] Load-testing tools have difficulty measuring render-response time, since they generally have no concept of what happens within a node apart from recognizing a period of time where there is no activity 'on the wire'.
[src:gatling/software-performance-testing] To measure render response time, it is generally necessary to include functional test scripts as part of the performance test scenario.
[src:gatling/software-performance-testing] Many load testing tools do not offer this feature.
[src:gatling/software-performance-testing] It is critical to detail performance specifications (requirements) and document them in any performance test plan.
[src:gatling/software-performance-testing] Ideally, this is done during the requirements development phase of any system development project, prior to any design effort.
[src:gatling/software-performance-testing] See Performance Engineering for more details.
[src:gatling/software-performance-testing] The performance specification in terms of response time, concurrency, etc. is usually captured in a Service Level Agreement (SLA).
[src:gatling/software-performance-testing] Alternatively, the performance of a test case can be compared against its previous execution in order to identify regressions.
[src:gatling/software-performance-testing] Since performance measurements are non-deterministic, capturing performance regressions requires appropriate repetition of the performance tests workload and appropriate statistical testing.
[src:gatling/software-performance-testing] Additionally, performance testing is frequently used as part of the process of performance profile tuning.
[src:gatling/software-performance-testing] The idea is to identify the bottleneck – the part of the system which, if it is made to respond faster, will result in the overall system running faster.
[src:gatling/software-performance-testing] Without such instrumentation one might have to have to rely on system monitoring.
[src:gatling/software-performance-testing] Performance testing can be performed across the web, and even done in different parts of the country, since it is known that the response times of the internet itself vary regionally.
[src:gatling/software-performance-testing] It can also be done in-house, although routers would then need to be configured to introduce the lag that would typically occur on public networks.
[src:gatling/software-performance-testing] Loads should be introduced to the system from realistic points.
[src:gatling/software-performance-testing] It is always helpful to have a statement of the likely peak number of users that might be expected to use the system at peak times.
[src:gatling/software-performance-testing] If there can also be a statement of what constitutes the maximum allowable 95 percentile response time, then an injector configuration could be used to test whether the proposed system met that specification.
[src:gatling/software-performance-testing] A stable build of the system which must resemble the production environment as closely as is possible.
[src:gatling/software-performance-testing] To ensure consistent results, the performance testing environment should be isolated from other environments, such as user acceptance testing (UAT) or development.
[src:gatling/software-performance-testing] As a best practice it is always advisable to have a separate performance testing environment resembling the production environment as much as possible.
[src:gatling/software-performance-testing] In performance testing, it is often crucial for the test conditions to be similar to the expected actual use.
[src:gatling/software-performance-testing] However, in practice this is hard to arrange and not wholly possible, since production systems are subjected to unpredictable workloads.
[src:gatling/software-performance-testing] Test workloads may mimic occurrences in the production environment as far as possible, but only in the simplest systems can one exactly replicate this workload variability.
[src:gatling/software-performance-testing] Loosely-coupled architectural implementations (e.g.: SOA) have created additional complexities with performance testing.
[src:gatling/software-performance-testing] To truly replicate production-like states, enterprise services or assets that share a common infrastructure or platform require coordinated performance testing, with all consumers creating production-like transaction volumes and load on shared infrastructures or platforms.
[src:gatling/software-performance-testing] It is critical to the cost performance of a new system that performance test efforts begin at the inception of the development project and extend through to deployment.
[src:gatling/software-performance-testing] The later a performance defect is detected, the higher the cost of remediation.
[src:gatling/software-performance-testing] This is true in the case of functional testing, but even more so with performance testing, due to the end-to-end nature of its scope.
[src:gatling/software-performance-testing] It is crucial for a performance test team to be involved as early as possible, because it is time-consuming to acquire and prepare the testing environment and other key performance requisites.
[src:gatling/software-performance-testing] This part of performance testing mainly deals with creating/scripting the work flows of key identified business processes.
[src:gatling/software-performance-testing] This can be done using a wide variety of tools.
[src:gatling/software-performance-testing] Each of the tools mentioned in the above list (which is not exhaustive nor complete) either employs a scripting language (C, Java, JS) or some form of visual representation (drag and drop) to create and simulate end user work flows.
[src:gatling/software-performance-testing] Most of the tools allow for something called "Record & Replay", where in the performance tester will launch the testing tool, hook it on a browser or thick client and capture all the network transactions which happen between the client and server.
[src:gatling/software-performance-testing] In doing so a script is developed which can be enhanced/modified to emulate various business scenarios.
[src:gatling/software-performance-testing] This forms the other face of performance testing.
[src:gatling/software-performance-testing] With performance monitoring, the behavior and response characteristics of the application under test are observed.
[src:gatling/software-performance-testing] As a first step, the patterns generated by these 4 parameters provide a good indication on where the bottleneck lies.
[src:gatling/software-performance-testing] To determine the exact root cause of the issue, software engineers use tools such as profilers to measure what parts of a device or software contribute most to the poor performance, or to establish throughput levels (and thresholds) for maintained acceptable response time.
[src:gatling/software-performance-testing] Usually, a separate PC acts as a test conductor, coordinating and gathering metrics from each of the injectors and collating performance data for reporting purposes.
[src:gatling/software-performance-testing] The usual sequence is to ramp up the load: to start with a few virtual users and increase the number over time to a predetermined maximum.
[src:gatling/software-performance-testing] The test result shows how the performance varies with the load, given as number of users vs. response time.
[src:gatling/software-performance-testing] Various tools are available to perform such tests.
[src:gatling/software-performance-testing] Tools in this category usually execute a suite of tests which emulate real users against the system.
