[src:gatling/software-performance-testing] Analytical Performance Modeling is a method to model the behavior of a system in a spreadsheet.
[src:gatling/software-performance-testing] The model is fed with measurements of transaction resource demands (CPU, disk I/O, LAN, WAN), weighted by the transaction-mix (business transactions per hour).
[src:gatling/software-performance-testing] The weighted transaction resource demands are added up to obtain the hourly resource demands and divided by the hourly resource capacity to obtain the resource loads.
[src:gatling/software-performance-testing] Using the response time formula (R=S/(1-U), R=response time, S=service time, U=load), response times can be calculated and calibrated with the results of the performance tests.
[src:gatling/software-performance-testing] Analytical performance modeling allows evaluation of design options and system sizing based on actual or anticipated business use.
[src:gatling/software-performance-testing] It is therefore much faster and cheaper than performance testing, though it requires thorough understanding of the hardware platforms.
[src:gatling/software-performance-testing] **Identify Performance Acceptance Criteria.** Identify the response time, throughput, and resource-use goals and constraints.
[src:gatling/software-performance-testing] In general, response time is a user concern, throughput is a business concern, and resource use is a system concern.
[src:gatling/software-performance-testing] Additionally, identify project success criteria that may not be captured by those goals and constraints; for example, using performance tests to evaluate which combination of configuration settings will result in the most desirable performance characteristics.
[src:gatling/software-performance-testing] **Plan and Design Tests.** Identify key scenarios, determine variability among representative users and how to simulate that variability, define test data, and establish metrics to be collected.
[src:gatling/software-performance-testing] Consolidate this information into one or more models of system usage to implemented, executed, and analyzed.
[src:gatling/software-performance-testing] **Configure the Test Environment.** Prepare the test environment, tools, and resources necessary to execute each strategy, as features and components become available for test.
[src:gatling/software-performance-testing] Ensure that the test environment is instrumented for resource monitoring as necessary.
[src:gatling/software-performance-testing] **Implement the Test Design.** Develop the performance tests in accordance with the test design.
[src:gatling/software-performance-testing] **Execute the Test.** Run and monitor your tests.
[src:gatling/software-performance-testing] Validate the tests, test data, and results collection.
[src:gatling/software-performance-testing] Execute validated tests for analysis while monitoring the test and the test environment.
[src:gatling/software-performance-testing] **Analyze Results, Tune, and Retest.** Analyze, consolidate, and share results data.
